    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.24-26_0001b"/>
                
                <note type="curatorial">Missouri Collection</note>
                
                <fw type="letterhead">
                    <del>"CARABAS"
                        <lb/>
                    SAUGATUCK
                        <lb/>
                    CONNECTICUT</del>
                </fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        "Bonniebrook"
                        Day Post Office
                        via Reed's Spring
                        Mo.
                        December 21 1937
                    </dateline>
                
                    <salute>Dear Poet <figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure></salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Mrs. Martyn wrote to me what yo<unclear>u</unclear> said about me and my possible "Memoirs". And I must tell you how heartening it was, coming into my solitude from such as you&#8212;a voice crying in the wilderness--and such a voice: -- meaning all the more to me in my spell-bound state. I have been completely forest-taken since the death of my divine mother in the spring. She knew your exquisite mother, too. and told me adorable things of her. I came too late.</p>
                
                <p>--I can not budge from the woods. Cities seem such "fiddling work" compared with the immense meaning of the forest.</p> <figure><figDesc>Two kewpies</figDesc></figure>
                
                    <fw type="curatorial">24</fw>
                   
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.24-26_0001a"/>
                
                <p>My poet brother, "Clink" is with me, an illuminating companion of my reading. He is an elf, or an <hi rend="underline">ouph</hi>, with a leprechaun sort of wit that startles and waylays. But you will know him. I don't give up your coming--you and that wonderful wife of yours. I've tried to bring it about through your neighbors. The Horines. --Please make it happen when Bonniebrook awakens again to the melting mood of the seasons. You were working on a new book last summer when I tried to get you. Is it out?</p>
                
                <p>I have just heard from Mr. Putnam of Macmillans, saying that your voice has been raised for me there. This aliveness of yours in my behalf projects life into my state which can, at present, lapse into a sort of twilight of unreality where <add>enterprises</add> <figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure> <figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure> lose the name of action."--</p>
                
                <p>I am gathering my story into form, however This that the New York literary agent wants to weild (there are two of them who ask for it) would be suitable, he thinks, for magazine first, book after.--I have piles of note-books which would make another book, or books. These
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.24-26_0002c"/>
                    
                    are a record of my interior life and would
                    
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.24-26_0003a"/>
                    
                    <fw type="authorial">3</fw>
                
                    be more for people with curiosity about a creature always involved in letters and art. Of course, a lot of drawings go with both kinds of book--</p>
                
                <p>Well, thanks and thanks. I shall always remember when we met in New York and I heard you read a memorable poem in a memorable voice.</p> 
                
                <p>Let us meet next in Bonniebrook.</p>
                <closer>                
                    <salute>Yours very much</salute>
                    <figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure> <signed>Rose O'Neill</signed>
                </closer>
                
                <postscript>
                    <p>I enclose a photo of a portrait I was lucky enough to make of my mother. I have been getting poems about her. <del>my mother</del><add><figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure></add> = and I am caring most about that just now. I put the latest one here. It is rather <unclear reason="missing"/></p>
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.17.24-26_0003b"/>
                
                    <lg><l>To Oblivion.</l>
                    <l>Take all these other ladies if you must</l>
                    <l>Scatter their sweet names and pretty dust</l>
                    <l>Let the wind take them, and the sand.</l>
                    <l>Let Troy forget:</l>
                    <l>But let this lady stand</l>
                    <l>Let this one lady be what never dies&#8212;</l>
                    <l>Be history. Oh, heart!</l>
                    <l>Oh eyes!<figure><figDesc>Drawing of a wing</figDesc></figure></l></lg>
                    
                    <lg><l>Question other heroes if you must,</l>
                    <l>Let glorious inscriptions go to rust</l>
                    <l>And undo noble deeds with doubt.</l>
                    <l>Let Rome forget.</l>
                    <l>But let this one hold out.</l>
                    <l>Oh, hold this <add>hero</add> back from Time's abyss:</l>
                    <l>Oh look: Oh wonder!</l>
                    <l>Oh remember this!</l></lg>
                    
                    <milestone unit="section"/><ab>===</ab>
                    
                    <lg><l>Another</l>
                    <l>How many times I left you, oh my Dove.</l>
                    <l>You and your last heroic look</l>
                    <l>That followed long the renegade of love,</l>
                    <l>You smiling after&#8212; patient by a brook.</l></lg>
                    
                    <lg><l>Now you the goer &#8212; patient as before</l>
                    <l>But in departure looking back at me.</l>
                    <l>I cannot leave you any more</l>
                    <l>Since you have left me utterly.</l></lg>
                </postscript>
                
            </div1>
            
            
